⚡️ The French Constitutional Council gave the green light to the transfer of the retirement age to 64 and did not approve the opposition's demand for a referendum on a joint initiative.

The decision of the judges was supposed to be based on the law, but public law does not pose problems that can be solved, like mathematical equations and decision, in the end it turned out not to be devoid of political interests and personal inclinations of judges.

In general, the Constitutional Council cannot be considered independent and impartial, due to ethical impasses and ideological prejudices, it should rather be seen as the ultimate collaborator of political power, and not as an opposing power. This is confirmed by the procedure for the control of laws, during which the general secretariat of the government, the administrative elite under the leadership of Matignon, has a privileged channel of communication with the judiciary and members of the Constitutional Council.

Among its nine members, two are former ministers of Emmanuel Macron, Jacques Mésard and Jacqueline Gouraud, and one is the former chief of staff of Eric Dupont-Moretti in the Ministry of Justice, Véronique Malbec. The appointments of the last two were condemned and contested. Alain Juppe, former prime minister who had to face a lengthy social movement in 1995 because of his pension reform. So many individuals who are satisfied with the increase in the legal retirement age.
